To my eye, most of these look like clear improvements that should be uncontroversial. I commented on other that might require more thought or where follow-up golfing is possible.

You didn't mark this ready for review yet. I still decided to leave a few comments; hope they helpful.

To my eye, most of these look like clear improvements that should be uncontroversial. I commented on other that might require more thought or where follow-up golfing is possible.
Can you move this into the `fapply`? If possible, I'd find this even nicer.

I'm a bit puzzled by this change: does the `apply` create two goals?
The way the code is indented, it looks like there is only one. (I didn't look at it in the infoview.)
The `apply` creates two goals, but one gets solved by unification, while solving the first one.  So, there are two goals when the `rw` is done, and one of them gets solved "at a distance".
Same question for this comment.
As above.
(If you want to further golf: could/should the `constructor; rw; exact` simply become one `exact`?)
Maybe, I was just interested in making a minimal set of changes to show the effect of a linter that I am testing out.  For this reason, I tried to make the changes as "syntactical" as possible.
Can the `exact` be inlined into the refine; would that be preferable?
Same as above: just "syntactical" changes.
This type of change looked odd to me, at first sight: upon second thought, it makes sense!
Yes, just to be completely explicit: the `rfl` is solving the case `n = 0` and the parentheses limit the scope of the `` to not extend beyond the first goal.
On its own merits (i.e., ignoring the multi-goal linter), I'm not sure if this change is an improvement.
I'd like to better understand where the `rfl` goal comes from: is it a side goal of an rw, or a second independent goal?
`negSucc_ediv` creates a side-goal of `0 < (2 ^ n)` and `rfl` closes the main goal (which is `-[m / 2 ^ n+1] = -(div m (2 ^ n) + 1)`).
Similarly this `rfl`: a side goal or not?
`map_permutationsAux2' id` creates 2 side-goals, each `map_id` creates one more and `rfl` closes the main goal.
Good find!
I'm on the fence if the `any_goals` => `repeat` change is better.

```suggestion
    rw [List.eq_replicate.mpr rfl, h, prod_replicate, one_pow]
```
I get why this was linted this way, but it seems unnecessary. The 2nd goal is just a bounding function waiting to get described by the next line.
I have been using `on_goal` sometimes as a place-holder for something where maybe the linter should be manually silenced.  I'll leave this comment visible, in case someone else wants to chime in.
Perhaps the linter shouldn't add `on_goal` when the additional goals are terms of `Type` and not `Prop`.
This is probably a good heuristic, though I would limit the use of this heuristic to theorems.  Again, I'll leave this up for further comments.
Could be `on_goal 2 => exact ReflTransGen.single rfl` removing the previous `swap`.
I tried to recycle as much as possible the original syntax.  I would prefer this change to be a separate PR.

```suggestion
  induction s
   contradiction
   rfl
```
